<DOC><DOCNO> AP901204-0170 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NY-12-04-90 2243EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Panama-Colonel     12-04 0201</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Panama-Colonel,0216</SECOND><HEAD>Colonel Jailed as Plotter Flees Panamanian Jail</HEAD><DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A retired army colonel, arrested inOctober on charges of plotting against President Guillermo Endara'sgovernment, broke jail Tuesday and fled in a helicopter, governmentsources and his lawyer said.   Former Col. Eduardo Herrera Hassan escaped from Naos Island inthe Pacific Ocean and flew to the Tinajitas military barracks onthe outskirts of Panama City, an official at the attorney general'soffice said.   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he hadno details and did not know what Herrera was doing at the barracks.   Herrera served in the now disbanded Defense Forces of ousteddictator Manuel Antonio Noriega.   Following his arrest on charges of plotting against the securityof the state, he was held for trial at Nao, a small resort islandthat also has a jail.   Rafael Rodriguez, Herrera's lawyer, confirmed in a liveinterview with the private radio station La Exitosa that Herrerafled the island, but refused to elaborate.   A U.S. military invasion of Panama deposed Noriega in December1989 and he was taken to Miami, where he is awaiting trial on drugtrafficking and money laundering charges.   Endara's government succeeded Noriega the day after theinvasion.</TEXT></DOC>